sec.p:
Supersymmetric (SUSY) GUT models are currently severely constrained by the non-observation of proton decay through dimension-5 operators from colored Higgsino exchange [33,34], the most stringent bound being on the $p	o K^+ 
u$ mode [35]. This constraint is imminent in SUSY renormalizable $SO(10)$ GUT models, because natural unification of the top and bottom quark Yukawa couplings requires $	an eta\sim50$. For such large $	an eta$, right-handed dimension-5 operators $E^cU^cU^cD^c$ give a significant contribution to the $p	o K^+ ar{
u}_	au$ decay [36], and it is hard to realize a cancellation in the $E^cU^cU^cD^c$ operators’ contribution and that of left-handed dimension-5 operators $QQQL$ to the $p	o K^+ ar{
u}_	au$ decay and a cancellation in the $QQQL$ operators’ contributions to the $p	o K^+ ar{
u}_\mu$ decay. Besides, it is impossible to enhance the colored Higgsino mass well above $2	imes10^{16}$ GeV (by some adjustment of the mass spectrum of GUT-scale particles that modifies the unification conditions) because the $SO(10)$ gauge coupling would become non-perturbative immediately above the thresholds of the components of rank-5 ${ f 126}+{ f \overline{126}}$ fields.1 Although one can increase the soft SUSY-breaking scale to suppress dimension-5 proton decays, the higher the SUSY particle masses, the more the naturalness of the electroweak scale is lost. In this situation, it is worth recalling that it is the fundamental Yukawa couplings $	ilde{Y}_{10}$, $	ilde{Y}_{126}$, and $	ilde{Y}_{120}$ that determine the coefficients of the dimension-5 operators. There may be a texture of the fundamental Yukawa couplings that suppresses dimension-5 proton decays and at the same time reproduces the correct quark and lepton Yukawa couplings and neutrino mass matrix. Specifically, as the up quark Yukawa coupling is a specially small Yukawa coupling in the minimal SUSY SM (MSSM) with $	an eta\sim50$, if those components of the Yukawa matrices $	ilde{Y}_{10}$, $	ilde{Y}_{126}$, and $	ilde{Y}_{120}$ responsible for dimension-5 proton decays are related to the up quark Yukawa coupling, then dimension-5 proton decays are maximally suppressed. The above idea has been sought in Refs. [37,38] based on the model that includes single ${ f 10}$, single ${ f \overline{126}}$, and single ${ f 120}$ fields [17–19].

We consider a SUSY $SO(10)$ GUT model that contains fields in ${\bf 10}$, ${\bf 126}$, ${\bf \overline{126}}$, and ${\bf 120}$ representations, denoted by $H$, $\Delta$, $\overline{\Delta}$, and $\Sigma$, and three matter fields in the 16 representation, denoted by $\Psi_i$ ($i$ is the flavor index). The model also contains fields in ${\bf 210}$ and ${\bf 45}$ representations, denoted by $\Phi$ and $A$, which are responsible for breaking the $SU(5)$ subgroup of $SO(10)$. The most general renormalizable Yukawa couplings are given by
(1)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
W_{\rm Yukawa}\ =\ (\tilde{Y}_{10})_{ij}\,\Psi_i H\Psi_j+(\tilde{Y}_{126})_{ij}\,\Psi_i\overline{\Delta}\Psi_j+(\tilde{Y}_{120})_{ij}\,\Psi_i\Sigma\Psi_j,
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $\tilde{Y}_{10}$ and $\tilde{Y}_{126}$ are $3\times3$ complex symmetric matrices and $\tilde{Y}_{120}$ is a $3\times3$ complex antisymmetric matrix, and $i,j$ are the flavor indices that correspond to that of $\Psi_i$. The electroweak-breaking-Higgs fields of the MSSM, $H_u$ and $H_d$, are linear combinations of (${\bf 1}$, ${\bf2}$, $\pm\frac{1}{2}$) components of $H$, $\Delta$, $\overline{\Delta}$, $\Sigma$, and $\Phi$. Accordingly, the Yukawa coupling for up-type quarks, $Y_u$, for down-type quarks, $Y_d$, and for charged leptons, $Y_e$, and the Dirac Yukawa coupling for neutrinos, $Y_D$, are derived as
(2)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
W_{\rm Yukawa}\ \supset\ (Y_u)_{ij}\,Q_i H_u U_i^c+(Y_d)_{ij}\,Q_i H_d D_i^c+(Y_e)_{ij}\,L_i H_d E_i^c+(Y_D)_{ij}\,L_i H_u N_i^c,\label{susyyukawa}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $Y_u$, $Y_d$, $Y_e$, and $Y_D$ are given by
(3)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_u & = & Y_{10}+r_2\,Y_{126}+r_3\,Y_{120},\label{yu}\\
\end{eqnarray}
$$
(4)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_d & = & r_1\left(Y_{10}+Y_{126}+Y_{120}\right)\!,\label{yd}\\
\end{eqnarray}
$$
(5)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_e & = & r_1\left(Y_{10}-3Y_{126}+r_e\,Y_{120}\right)\!,\label{ye}\\
\end{eqnarray}
$$
(6)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_D & = & Y_{10}-3r_2\,Y_{126}+r_D\,Y_{120}\label{ydirac}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
at an $SO(10)$ breaking scale. Here, $Y_{10}\propto\tilde{Y}_{10}$, $Y_{126}\propto\tilde{Y}_{126}$, $Y_{120}\propto\tilde{Y}_{120}$, and $r_1,r_2,r_3,r_e,r_D$ are numbers. By a phase redefinition, we take $r_1$ to be real positive.

Majorana mass for the right-handed neutrinos is obtained as $(Y_{126})_{ij}\,\overline{v}_R\,N_i^c N_j^c$, where $\overline{v}_R$ denotes $\overline{\Delta}$’s VEV. Integrating out $N_i^c$ yields an effective operator $L_iH_uL_jH_u$, which we call the Type-1 seesaw contribution. Additionally, the (1, 3, 1) component of $\overline{\Delta}$ mixes with that of $E$ after $SO(10)$ breaking. Integrating out the (1, 3, 1) components yields an effective operator $L_iH_uL_jH_u$, which we call the Type-2 seesaw contribution. This paper centers on the case where the Type-2 seesaw contribution dominates over the Type-1, in which case the Wilson coefficient of the Weinberg operator $(C_\nu)_{ij} L_iH_uL_jH_u$ satisfies
(7)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
(C_\nu)_{ij} \ \propto \ (Y_{126})_{ij}\label{cnu}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
at an $SO(10)$ breaking scale. In Appendix B, we present an example of VEV configurations that realize the dominance of the Type-2 seesaw contribution.

$H$, $\Delta$, $\bar{\Delta}$, $\Sigma$, and $\Phi$ contain pairs of (3, 1, $-\frac{1}{3}$) and (${\bf \overline{3}}$, 1, $\frac{1}{3}$) components, which we call “colored Higgs fields” and denote by $H_C^A$ and $\overline{H}_C^B$ ($A,B$ are labels), respectively. Exchange of $H_C^A,\overline{H}_C^B$ gives rise to dimension-5 operators inducing a proton decay. Those couplings of $H_C^A,\overline{H}^B_C$ which contribute to such operators are
(8)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
W_{\rm Yukawa} & \supset & \sum_A\bigg[ \frac{1}{2}(Y_L^A)_{ij}\,Q_i H_C^A Q_j + (\overline{Y}^A_L)_{ij}\,Q_i \overline{H}^A_C L_j \nonumber \\
& & \qquad + \ (Y_R^A)_{ij}\,E^c_i H_C^A U^c_j + (\overline{Y}_R^A)_{ij}\,U^c_i \overline{H}_C^A D^c_j \bigg],\label{coloredHiggsYukawa}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $\overline{Y}_L^A$, $Y_R^A$, and $\overline{Y}^A_R$ are proportional to $Y_{10}$, $Y_{126}$, or $Y_{120}$, and $Y_L^A$ are proportional to $Y_{10}$ or $Y_{126}$. After integrating out $H^A_C,\overline{H}^B_C$, we get effective dimension-5 operators contributing to proton decay,
(9)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
-W_5 \ = \ \frac{1}{2}C_{5L}^{ijkl}\,(Q_k Q_{l})(Q_i L_{j}) + C_{5R}^{ijkl}\,E^c_k U^c_{l} U^c_i D^c_{j}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
(in the first term, isospin indices are summed in each bracket), where
(10)$$
\begin{align}
C_{5L}^{ijkl}(\mu=\mu_{H_C})&= \left. \sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}
\left\{(Y_L^A)_{kl}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{ij}
-\frac{1}{2}(Y_L^A)_{li}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{kj}-\frac{1}{2}(Y_L^A)_{ik}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{lj}\right\}\right|_{\mu=\mu_{H_C}},\label{c5lgeneral}\\
\end{align}
$$
(11)$$
\begin{align}
C_{5R}^{ijkl}(\mu=\mu_{H_C})&= \left. \sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}
\left\{(Y_R^A)_{kl}(\overline{Y}_R^B)_{ij}-(Y_R^A)_{ki}(\overline{Y}_R^B)_{lj}\right\}\right|_{\mu=\mu_{H_C}},\label{c5rgeneral}
\end{align}
$$
${\cal M}_{H_C}$ denotes the mass matrix for $H^A_C,\overline{H}^B_C$, and $\mu_{H_C}$ is taken around the eigenvalues of ${\cal M}_{H_C}$.

The contribution of the $C_{5L}^{ijkl}(Q_k Q_{l})(Q_i L_{j})$ term to the $p\to K^+\bar{\nu}_\alpha$ ($\alpha=e,\mu,\tau$) decays is given by
(12)$$
\begin{align}
\Gamma(p\to K^+\bar{\nu}_\alpha)\vert_{{\rm from} \,C_{5L}}
& = {\cal C}
\left\vert \beta_H(\mu_{\rm had})\frac{1}{f_\pi}\left\{
\left(1+\frac{D}{3}+F\right)C_{LL}^{s\alpha \,ud}(\mu_{\rm had})+\frac{2D}{3}C_{LL}^{d\alpha \,us}(\mu_{\rm had})\right\}
\right\vert^2.\label{ptoknuLformula}
\end{align}
$$

Here, ${\cal C}=\frac{m_N}{64\pi}\left(1-\frac{m_K^2}{m_N^2}\right)^2$, with $m_N$ denoting the nucleon mass and $m_K$ the kaon mass, $\alpha_H,\beta_H$ denote hadronic matrix elements, $D,F$ are parameters of the baryon chiral Lagrangian, and $C_{LL}$ are Wilson coefficients of the effective Lagrangian, $-{\cal L}_6\supset C_{LL}^{ijkl}(\psi_{u_Lk}\psi_{d_Ll})(\psi_{d_Li}\psi_{\nu_Lj})$, where $\psi$ denotes an SM Weyl spinor and the spinor index is summed in each bracket. The Wilson coefficients $C_{LL}$ satisfy2
(13)$$
\begin{align}
C_{LL}^{s\alpha\,ud}(\mu_{\rm had})= A_{LL}(\mu_{\rm had},\mu_{\rm SUSY})
\frac{M_{\widetilde{W}}}{m_{\tilde{q}}^2}
\,{\cal F}\,
g_2^2\left(C_{5L}^{s\alpha\,ud}-C_{5L}^{u\alpha\, ds}\right)\Big\vert_{\mu=\mu_{\rm SUSY}},
\end{align}
$$
(14)$$
\begin{align}
C_{LL}^{d\alpha\,su}(\mu_{\rm had})= A_{LL}(\mu_{\rm had},\mu_{\rm SUSY})
\frac{M_{\widetilde{W}}}{m_{\tilde{q}}^2}
\,{\cal F}\,
g_2^2\left(C_{5L}^{d\alpha\, us}-C_{5L}^{u\alpha\, ds}\right)\Big\vert_{\mu=\mu_{\rm SUSY}}.
\end{align}
$$

The contribution of the $C_{5L}^{ijkl}(Q_k Q_{l})(Q_i L_{j})$ term to the $p\to K^0e_\beta^+$ $(e_\beta=e,\mu)$ decays is given by
(17)$$
\begin{align}
&\Gamma(p\to K^0e_\beta^+)
\ = \ {\cal C}\,
\left\vert \beta_H(\mu_{\rm had})\frac{1}{f_\pi}
\left(1-D+F\right)\overline{C}_{LL}^{u\beta \,us}(\mu_{\rm had})
\right\vert^2.\label{ptokmuformula}
\end{align}
$$

The contribution of the $C_{5R}^{ijkl}\,E^c_k U^c_{l} U^c_i D^c_{j}$ term to the $p\to K^+\bar{\nu}_\tau$ decay is given by
(20)$$
\begin{align}
\Gamma(p\to K^+\bar{\nu}_\tau)\vert_{{\rm from} \,C_{5R}}
& = {\cal C}
\left\vert \alpha_H(\mu_{\rm had})\frac{1}{f_\pi}\left\{
\left(1+\frac{D}{3}+F\right)C_{RL}^{ud \,\tau s}(\mu_{\rm had})+\frac{2D}{3}C_{RL}^{us \,\tau d}(\mu_{\rm had})
\right\}\right\vert^2.\label{ptoknuRformula}
\end{align}
$$

$A_{RL}(\mu_{\rm had},\mu_{\rm SUSY})$ accounts for SM RG corrections. The Wilson coefficients $C_{5R}$ are related to the colored Higgs Yukawa couplings as
(23)$$
\begin{align}
C_{5R}^{ud\tau t}(\mu_{\rm SUSY}) & =
A_R^{\tau t}(\mu_{\rm SUSY},\mu_{H_C})\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\left.
\left\{(Y_R^A)_{\tau t}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{ud}-(Y_R^A)_{\tau u}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{td}\right\}\right|_{\mu=\mu_{H_C}}\!,\label{c5r1}\\
\end{align}
$$
(24)$$
\begin{align}
C_{5R}^{us\tau t}(\mu_{\rm SUSY}) & =
A_R^{\tau t}(\mu_{\rm SUSY},\mu_{H_C})\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\left.
\left\{(Y_R^A)_{\tau t}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{us}-(Y_R^A)_{\tau u}(\overline{Y}_R^B)_{ts}\right\}\right|_{\mu=\mu_{H_C}}\!,\label{c5r2}
\end{align}
$$
where $A_R^{\tau t}(\mu_{\rm SUSY},\mu_{H_C})$ accounts for MSSM RG corrections.

The flavor-dependent terms in Eqs. (15), (16), (19), (23), and (24) are related to the fundamental Yukawa couplings $Y_{10}$, $Y_{126}$, and $Y_{120}$ as follows. Since $Y_L^A$ is defined as $W_{\rm Yukawa} \supset (Y_L^A)_{ij}\,Q_i H_C^A Q_j$, its flavor indices are symmetric and thus $Y_L^A$ is not proportional to $Y_{120}$. Therefore, we can write, without loss of generality, with $\alpha=e,\mu,\tau$ and $\beta=e,\mu$,
(25)$$
\begin{align}
\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\Big\{(Y_L^A)_{ud}(&\overline{Y}^B_L)_{s\alpha}-(Y_L^A)_{ds}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{u\alpha}\Big\}
\nonumber\\
&=\frac{1}{M_{H_C}}
\big[
a\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{10})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{10})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + b\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{126})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{126})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + c\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{120})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{120})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + d\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{10})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{10})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + e\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{126})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{126})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
&
\qquad \qquad + f\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L d_L}(Y_{120})_{s_L\alpha_L}-(Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}(Y_{120})_{u_L\alpha_L}\right\}\big],
\label{yyl1}
\end{align}
$$
(26)$$
\begin{multline}
\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\left\{(Y_L^A)_{us}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{d\alpha}-(Y_L^A)_{ds}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{u\alpha}\right\} \\
={\rm (Above \ expression \ with \ the \ exchange} \ d_L\leftrightarrow s_L),\label{yyl2}
\end{multline}
$$
(27)$$
\begin{align}
\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\Big\{(Y_L^A)_{us}(&\overline{Y}^B_L)_{u\beta}-(Y_L^A)_{uu}(\overline{Y}^B_L)_{s\beta}\Big\}
\nonumber\\
&=\frac{1}{M_{H_C}}
\big[
a\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{10})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{10})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{10})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad +b\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{126})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{10})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{126})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + c\left\{(Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{120})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{10})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{120})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + d\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{10})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{126})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{10})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + e\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{126})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{126})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{126})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\}
\nonumber\\
&
\qquad \qquad + f\left\{(Y_{126})_{u_L s_L}(Y_{120})_{u_L\beta_L}-(Y_{126})_{u_L u_L}(Y_{120})_{s_L\beta_L}\right\}\big],\label{yyl3}
\end{align}
$$
where $M_{H_C}$ denotes a typical value of the eigenvalues of ${\cal M}_{H_C}$, and $a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,j$ are numbers determined from the colored Higgs mass matrix [40–45]. Here, $(Y_{10})_{u_Ld_L}$ denotes the $(1,1)$-component of $Y_{10}$ in the term $(Y_{10})_{ij}\,\Psi_i H \Psi_j$ in the flavor basis where the left-handed up-type quark component of $\Psi_i$ has the diagonalized up-type quark Yukawa coupling, and the left-handed down-type quark component of $\Psi_j$ has the diagonalized down-type quark Yukawa coupling. $(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}$, $(Y_{126})_{u_L d_L}$, and others are defined analogously. Since each of $Y_R^A,\overline{Y}_R^A$ is proportional to $Y_{10}$, $Y_{126}$, or $Y_{120}$, we can write
(28)$$
\begin{align}
\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\Big\{(Y_R^A)_{\tau t}(&\overline{Y}^B_R)_{ud}-(Y_R^A)_{\tau u}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{td}\Big\}
\nonumber\\
&=\frac{1}{M_{H_C}}
\big[
a\left\{(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{10})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{10})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{10})_{t_Rd_R}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + b\left\{(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{126})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{10})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{126})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + c\left\{(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{120})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{10})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{120})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + d\left\{(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{10})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{126})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{10})_{t_Rd_R}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + e\left\{(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{126})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{126})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{126})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + f\left\{(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{120})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{126})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{120})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}
\nonumber\\
& \qquad \qquad + g\left\{(Y_{120})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{10})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{120})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{10})_{t_Rd_R}\right\} \nonumber \\
& \qquad \qquad + h\left\{(Y_{120})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{126})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{120})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{126})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}
\nonumber\\
&
\qquad \qquad + j\left\{(Y_{120})_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_{120})_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_{120})_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_{120})_{t_Rd_R}\right\}\big],
\label{yyr1}
\end{align}
$$
(29)$$
\begin{multline}
\sum_{A,B}({\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1})_{AB}\left\{(Y_R^A)_{\tau t}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{us}-(Y_R^A)_{\tau u}(\overline{Y}^B_R)_{ts}\right\} \\
={\rm (Above \ expression \ with \ the \ replacement} \ d_R\to s_R),\label{yyr2}
\end{multline}
$$
where $a,b,c,d,e,f$ are the same numbers as in Eqs. (25)–(27).

First, focus on Eq. (28). We have $(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}+r_2(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}+r_3(Y_{120})_{\tau_R t_R}=y_t\times$ ($t_L$–$\tau_R$ part of the mixing matrix), and since $t_L$ and $\tau_R$ are both third-generation components, the $t_L$–$\tau_R$ part of the mixing matrix is almost maximal. The component $(Y_{120})_{\tau_R t_R}$ is suppressed compared to $(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}$, and $(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}$ because $Y_{120}$ is an antisymmetric matrix. Consequently, one or both of $(Y_{10})_{\tau_R t_R}$ and $(Y_{126})_{\tau_R t_R}$ are always on the order of the top quark Yukawa coupling $y_t$. Hence, in order to reduce the Yukawa coupling pair products in Eq. (28), it is necessary to reduce
(30)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
(Y_{10})_{u_R d_R}, \ \ \ (Y_{126})_{u_R d_R}, \ \ \ {\rm and} \ \ \ (Y_{120})_{u_R d_R}.
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Now focus on Eq. (29). For the same reason as above, we have to reduce
(31)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
(Y_{10})_{u_R s_R}, \ \ \ (Y_{126})_{u_R s_R}, \ \ \ {\rm and} \ \ \ (Y_{120})_{u_R s_R}.
\end{eqnarray}
$$

As a matter of fact, it is impossible to simultaneously reduce $(Y_{10})_{u_R s_R}$, $(Y_{126})_{u_R s_R}$, and $(Y_{120})_{u_R s_R}$ to $O(y_u)$. This is because Eq. (4) gives
(32)$$
\begin{align}
(Y_{10})_{u_R s_R}+(Y_{126})_{u_R s_R}+(Y_{120})_{u_R s_R} \ &= \ \frac{1}{r_1}(Y_d)_{u_R s_R}
\nonumber\\
&\simeq \ \frac{y_t}{y_b}y_s\times (s_L \mbox{--}
u_R \ {\rm part \ of \ the \ mixing \ matrix}),\label{ursr}
\end{align}
$$
where $r_1$ is estimated to be $y_b/y_t$ so that the top and bottom quark Yukawa couplings are reproduced. The $s_L \mbox{--} u_R \ {\rm part \ of \ the \ mixing \ matrix}$ is estimated to be the Cabibbo angle $\lambda\simeq0.22$, and thus we get $(Y_{10})_{u_R s_R}+(Y_{126})_{u_R s_R}+(Y_{120})_{u_R s_R}\simeq0.22\times\frac{y_t}{y_b}y_s$, which is much greater than the up quark Yukawa coupling $y_u$.

A way out is to adjust the colored Higgs mass matrix such that the coefficients $c,f$ in Eqs. (25)–(29) are zero,
(33)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
c=f=0.
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Unfortunately, at least one of $(Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}$, $(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}$, $(Y_{126})_{u_L s_L}$, and $(Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}$ is on the order of $V^{\rm ckm}_{cd}\,\frac{y_t}{y_b}y_s$, and consequently some of the Yukawa coupling pair products in Eqs. (25) and (26) cannot be suppressed to $O(y_u\,y_t)$ for all $\alpha$. This is seen from the two equalities
(34)$$
\begin{align}
&(Y_{10})_{s_L c_L}+(Y_{126})_{s_L c_L}+(Y_{120})_{s_L c_L} \ \simeq \ \frac{y_t}{y_b}y_s
\times (c_L \mbox{--}
s_R \ {\rm part \ of \ the \ mixing \ matrix)},\label{clsl}
\end{align}
$$
(35)$$
\begin{multline}
(Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}+(Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}-V^{\rm ckm}_{ud} \left\{ (Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}+(Y_{126})_{u_L s_L} \right\} \\
=\ V^{\rm ckm}_{cd} \left\{ (Y_{10})_{c_L s_L}+(Y_{126})_{c_L s_L} \right\}
+V^{\rm ckm}_{td} \left\{ (Y_{10})_{t_L s_L}+(Y_{126})_{t_L s_L} \right\}.\label{dlsl}
\end{multline}
$$

To sum up, in order to suppress dimension-5 proton decays, we have to reduce the following Yukawa couplings:
(36)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
&&(Y_{10})_{u_R d_R}, \ (Y_{126})_{u_R d_R}, \ (Y_{10})_{u_R s_R}, \ (Y_{126})_{u_R s_R}
\nonumber\\
&&(Y_{10})_{u_L d_L}, \ (Y_{126})_{u_L d_L}, \ (Y_{10})_{u_L u_L}, \ (Y_{126})_{u_L u_L}, \ (Y_{10})_{u_L s_L}, \ (Y_{126})_{u_L s_L}.\label{tobereduced}
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Given Eq. (37), the colored Higgs mass matrix is given by
(38)$$
\begin{align}
&W \supset \begin{pmatrix}
H^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})} & \overline{\Delta}^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,1)} & \Delta^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,1)} & \Delta^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})}_{(\overline{10},1,3)}
& \Phi^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})} & \Sigma^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,3)} & \Sigma^{(\overline{3},1,\frac{1}{3})}_{(\overline{10},1,1)}
\end{pmatrix}{\cal M}_{H_C}
\!\! \begin{pmatrix}
H^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})} \\ \Delta^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,1)} \\ \overline{\Delta}^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,1)} \\ \overline{\Delta}^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})}_{(10,1,3)}
\\ \Phi^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})} \\ \Sigma^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})}_{(6,1,3)} \\ \Sigma^{(3,1,-\frac{1}{3})}_{(10,1,1)}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align}
$$
where
(39)$$
\begin{multline}
{\cal M}_{H_C} = \\
\begin{pmatrix}
m_3 &\frac{ \lambda_3\Phi_2}{\sqrt{30}}-\frac{ \lambda_3\Phi_1}{\sqrt{10}} & -\frac{\lambda_4\Phi_1}{\sqrt{10}}-\frac{\lambda_4\Phi_2}{\sqrt{30}}
& -\sqrt{\frac{2}{15}}\lambda_4\Phi_3 & \frac{\lambda_4\overline{v}_R}{\sqrt{5}} & 0 & 0 \\
\frac{\lambda_4\Phi_2}{\sqrt{30}}-\frac{\lambda_4\Phi_1}{\sqrt{10}} & m_2+i\frac{\lambda_{21}}{\lambda_{19}}\frac{\lambda_6\Phi_2}{30\sqrt{2}} & 0 & 0 &0 &0 & 0 \\
-\frac{\lambda_3\Phi_1}{\sqrt{10}}-\frac{\lambda_3\Phi_2}{\sqrt{30}} & 0 & m_2-i\frac{\lambda_{21}}{\lambda_{19}}\frac{\lambda_6\Phi_2}{30\sqrt{2}} &\frac{\lambda_2\Phi_3}{15\sqrt{2}} & -\frac{\lambda_2\overline{v}_R}{10\sqrt{3}} & 0 & 0 \\
-\sqrt{\frac{2}{15}}\lambda_3\Phi_3 & 0 & \frac{\lambda_2\Phi_3}{15\sqrt{2}} & m_{66} & -\frac{\lambda_2\overline{v}_R}{5\sqrt{6}} & 0 & 0 \\
\frac{\lambda_3v_R}{\sqrt{5}} & 0 & -\frac{\lambda_2v_R}{10\sqrt{3}} & -\frac{\lambda_2v_R}{5\sqrt{6}} & m_{77} & 0 & 0 \\
-\lambda_{17}\frac{\Phi_3}{\sqrt{3}} & 0 & \lambda_{21}\frac{\Phi_3}{6\sqrt{5}} & \lambda_{21}\frac{\Phi_2}{3\sqrt{5}} & \frac{\lambda_{21}\overline{v}_R}{2\sqrt{15}} & m_{22} & \frac{2\lambda_{15}\Phi_3}{9} \\
-\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\lambda_{17}\Phi_2 & 0 & \lambda_{21}\frac{\Phi_2}{3\sqrt{10}} & \lambda_{21}\frac{\Phi_3}{3\sqrt{10}} &
\frac{\lambda_{21}\overline{v}_R}{2\sqrt{15}} & \frac{2\lambda_{15}\Phi_3}{9} & m_{33}
\end{pmatrix},\label{texture-coloredhiggs}
\end{multline}
$$
(40)$$
\begin{align}
m_{66} & = m_2+\lambda_2\bigg(\frac{\Phi_1}{10\sqrt{6}}+\frac{\Phi_2}{30\sqrt{2}}\bigg)-i\frac{\lambda_{21}}{\lambda_{19}}\frac{\lambda_6\Phi_2}{30\sqrt{2}},
\end{align}
$$
(41)$$
\begin{align}
m_{77} & = m_1+\lambda_1\bigg(\frac{\Phi_1}{\sqrt{6}}+\frac{\Phi_2}{3\sqrt{2}}+\frac{2\Phi_3}{3}\bigg)-i\frac{\lambda_{21}}{\lambda_{19}}\frac{\sqrt{2}\lambda_7\Phi_2}{15},
\end{align}
$$
(42)$$
\begin{align}
m_{22} & = m_6+\frac{1}{3}\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\lambda_{15}\Phi_1,
\end{align}
$$
(43)$$
\begin{align}
m_{33} & = m_6+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{9}\lambda_{15}\Phi_2.
\end{align}
$$

The Wilson coefficients of the terms $C_{5L}^{ijkl}(Q_k Q_{l})(Q_i L_{j})$ and $C_{5R}^{ijkl}E^c_k U^c_{l} U^c_i D^c_{j}$, which appear after integrating out the colored Higgs fields, are given by
(44)$$
\begin{multline}
C_{5L}^{ijkl}(\mu=\mu_{H_C}) = C_{5R}^{ijkl}(\mu=\mu_{H_C}) \\
= \begin{pmatrix}
(\tilde{Y}_{10})_{kl} & 0 & (\tilde{Y}_{126})_{kl} & (\tilde{Y}_{126})_{kl}
& 0 & (\tilde{Y}_{120})_{kl} & (\tilde{Y}_{120})_{kl}
\end{pmatrix}{\cal M}_{H_C}^{-1}
\begin{pmatrix}
(\tilde{Y}_{10})_{ij} \\ (\tilde{Y}_{126})_{ij} \\ 0 \\ 0
\\ 0 \\ (\tilde{Y}_{120})_{ij} \\ (\tilde{Y}_{120})_{ij}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{multline}
$$

First, we numerically calculate the MSSM Yukawa coupling matrices $Y_u,Y_d,Y_e$ at scale $\mu=2\times10^{16}$ GeV in the $\overline{{\rm DR}}$ scheme. We also calculate the flavor-dependent part of the RG corrections to the coefficient of the $L_i ({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1) L_j$ operator ($({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)$ is a component of $\overline{\Delta}$ and this operator originates from the $\Psi_i\overline{\Delta}\Psi_j$ operator) in the evolution from $\mu=2\times10^{16}$ GeV to $\mu=10^{13}$ GeV, and to the coefficient of the Weinberg operator in the evolution from $\mu=10^{13}$ GeV to $\mu=M_Z$, written as $R_{ij}$ and defined as $(C_\nu)_{ij}|_{\mu=M_Z}=c\sum_{k,l}R_{ik}R_{jl}(Y_{126})_{kl}|_{\mu=2\times10^{16}\,{\rm GeV}}$, where $c$ is a flavor-independent constant. Here, $10^{13}$ GeV is the typical scale of the mass of a $({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)$ particle that is integrated out to obtain the Weinberg operator (see Appendix B).6 In the calculation of the RG equations, we assume the following spectrum of the pole masses of SUSY particles for concreteness:
(45)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
&&m_{\widetilde{q}}=m_{\widetilde{u}^c}=m_{\widetilde{d}^c}=m_{\widetilde{\ell}}=m_{\widetilde{e}^c}=m_{H^0}=m_{H^\pm}=m_A=20\,{\rm TeV},
\nonumber\\
&&M_{\widetilde{g}}=M_{\widetilde{W}}=\mu_H=2\,{\rm TeV},
\ \ \ \ \ \ \tan\beta \ = \ 50.\label{massspectrum}
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Next, we fit the MSSM Yukawa couplings $Y_u,Y_d,Y_e$ and the neutrino mixing angles and mass differences with the fundamental Yukawa couplings $Y_{10},Y_{126},Y_{120}$ and the numbers $r_1,r_2,r_3,r_e$ according to Eqs. (3)–(5) and (7). Meanwhile, we minimize the following quantity:
(46)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{A=10,126}\,\left\{ \
\left|(Y_A)_{u_R d_R}\right|^2+\left|(Y_A)_{u_R s_R}\right|^2+\left|(Y_A)_{u_L d_L}\right|^2+\left|(Y_A)_{u_L u_L}\right|^2+\left|(Y_A)_{u_L s_L}\right|^2 \ \right\}\!.\label{tobeminimized}
\end{eqnarray}
$$

To facilitate the analysis, we concentrate on the parameter region where $r_3=0$ (which is compatible with any values of $r_1,r_2,r_e$ and Eq. (37)). Then, we obtain $(Y_{10})_{u_R\, j}+r_2(Y_{126})_{u_R\, j}\leq y_u$ and $(Y_{10})_{u_L\, j}+r_2(Y_{126})_{u_L\, j}\leq y_u$ for any flavor index $j$, and it becomes easier to reduce Eq. (46) to the order of the tiny up quark Yukawa coupling $y_u$. Given $r_3=0$, Eqs. (3)–(5) can be rearranged as follows: We fix the flavor basis such that the left-handed down-type quark components in $\Psi_i$ have diagonal $Y_d$ Yukawa coupling with real positive diagonal components. $Y_u$, which is still symmetric, is then written as8
(47)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_u=V_{\rm CKM}^{\rm T}
\begin{pmatrix}
y_u & 0 & 0 \\
0 & y_c \,e^{2i \,d_2} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & y_t \,e^{2i \,d_3}\\
\end{pmatrix}
V_{\rm CKM},\label{yu3}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $d_2,d_3$ are unknown phases. In the same flavor basis, $Y_d$ becomes
(48)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_d=\begin{pmatrix}
y_d & 0 & 0 \\
0 & y_s & 0 \\
0 & 0 & y_b \\
\end{pmatrix}
V_{dR},\label{yd3}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $V_{dR}$ is an unknown unitary matrix. From Eqs. (4) and (5), and the fact that $Y_{10}$ and $Y_{126}$ are symmetric and $Y_{120}$ is antisymmetric, we get
(49)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_{126} & =& \frac{1}{1-r_2}\left\{\frac{1}{r_1}\frac{1}{2}\left(Y_d+Y_d^{\rm T}\right)-Y_u\right\}\!,
\end{eqnarray}
$$
(50)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{1}{r_1}Y_e & = & Y_u-(3+r_2)Y_{126}+r_e\frac{1}{r_1}\frac{1}{2}\left(Y_d-Y_d^{\rm T}\right).
\end{eqnarray}
$$

We perform the singular value decomposition of $Y_e$ as
(51)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
Y_e = U_{eL}\begin{pmatrix}
y_e & 0 & 0 \\
0 & y_\mu & 0 \\
0 & 0 & y_\tau \\
\end{pmatrix}
U_{eR}^\dagger,
\end{eqnarray}
$$
and calculate the active neutrino mass matrix in the charged-lepton-diagonal basis as
(52)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
(M_\nu)_{\ell \ell'} \ \propto \ R_{\ell \ell} \ (U_{eL}^{\rm T}Y_{126}U_{eL})_{\ell\ell'} \
R_{\ell' \ell'}, \ \ \ \ \ \ \ell,\ell'=e,\mu,\tau,\label{mnumatching2}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $\ell,\ell'$ denote flavor indices for the left-handed charged leptons. Utilizing Eqs. (47)–(52), we perform the fitting as follows. We fix $y_u,y_c,y_t$ and the CKM matrix by the values in Table 1, while we vary $y_d/r_1$, $y_s/r_1$, $y_b/r_1$, the unknown phases $d_2,d_3$, the unknown unitary matrix $V_{dR}$, and the complex numbers $r_2,r_e$. Here we eliminate $r_1$ by requiring that the central value of the electron Yukawa coupling $y_e$ be reproduced. In this way, we try to reproduce the correct values of $y_d$, $y_s$, $y_\mu$, $y_\tau$, $\theta_{12}^{\rm pmns}$, $\theta_{13}^{\rm pmns}$, $\theta_{23}^{\rm pmns}$, and the neutrino mass difference ratio $\Delta m_{21}^2/\Delta m_{32}^2$. Specifically, we require $y_d,y_s$ to fit within their respective 3 $\sigma$ ranges, while we do not constrain $y_b$ because $y_b$ may be subject to sizable GUT-scale threshold corrections. We impose stringent restrictions on the values of neutrino mixing angles and mass differences, because we are primarily interested in the prediction for the neutrino Dirac CP phase from the condition that dimension-5 proton decays be suppressed as much as possible, and so it is essential to suppress variation of the other neutrino parameters. In particular, we require $\sin^2\theta_{12}^{\rm pmns}$, $\sin^2\theta_{13}^{\rm pmns}$, and $\Delta m_{21}^2/\Delta m_{32}^2$ to fit within their respective 1 $\sigma$ ranges as reported by NuFIT 4.1 [56,57]. We assume two narrow benchmark ranges of $\sin^2\theta_{23}^{\rm pmns}$, since the current experimental error of $\sin^2\theta_{23}^{\rm pmns}$ is too large. Only the normal hierarchy of the neutrino mass is considered because no good fitting is obtained with the inverted hierarchy. Finally, since the experimental errors of $y_\mu,y_\tau$ are tiny, we only require their reproduced values to fit within $\pm$0.1% of their central values. The constraints are summarized in Table 2.

We present plots of the fitting and minimization results obtained by the procedures of Sect. 4.1 on the planes of $\delta_{\rm pmns}$, $m_1$, $|m_{ee}|$ versus “maximal proton decay amplitude.” The “maximal proton decay amplitude” of the $p\to K^+\nu$ mode, $\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \nu)$, is defined as
(53)$$
\begin{multline}
\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \nu)^2 =
\left\{\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_\tau)|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5R}}+\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_\tau)|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5L}}\right\}^2 \\
+ \tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_\mu)^2|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5L}}+\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_e)^2|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5L}},
\label{maximal}
\end{multline}
$$
where
(54)$$
\begin{align}
\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_\tau)&|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5R}} \nonumber \\
& = y_ty_\tau\sum_{A,B}
\left|\bigg(1+\frac{D}{3}+F\bigg)\,V_{ts}^{\rm ckm}\,\{(Y_A)_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_B)_{u_Rd_R}-(Y_A)_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_B)_{t_Rd_R}\}\right. \nonumber \\
& \left. \qquad \qquad \quad + \frac{2D}{3}\,V_{td}^{\rm ckm}\,\{(Y_A)_{\tau_R t_R}(Y_B)_{u_Rs_R}-(Y_A)_{\tau_R u_R}(Y_B)_{t_Rs_R}\}\right|
\end{align}
$$
(sum over $A,B = (10,10), (10,126), (126,10), (126,126), (120,10), (120,126), (120,120)$),
(55)$$
\begin{multline}
\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \bar{\nu}_\alpha)|_{{\rm from} \ C_{5L}} \\
= g_2^2\sum_{A,B=10,126} \frac{3}{2}
\left|\bigg(1+\frac{D}{3}+F\bigg)(Y_A)_{u_L d_L}(Y_B)_{s_L \alpha_L}+\frac{2D}{3}(Y_A)_{u_L s_L}(Y_B)_{d_L \alpha_L}\right|,
\end{multline}
$$
with $\alpha=e,\mu,\tau$, and $y_t,y_\tau,g_2$ denoting the top and tau Yukawa couplings and the weak gauge coupling at soft SUSY-breaking scale $\mu_{\rm SUSY}$. The “maximal proton decay amplitudes” of the $p\to K^0 e^+_\beta$ modes, $\tilde{A}(p\to K^0 e^+_\beta)$, are defined as
(56)$$
\begin{equation}
\tilde{A}(p\to K^0 e^+_\beta) = g_2^2\sum_{A,B=10,126}\frac{3}{2}
(1-D+F)\left|(Y_A)_{u_L s_L}(Y_B)_{u_L \beta_L}-(Y_A)_{u_L u_L}(Y_B)_{s_L \beta_L}\right|,
\end{equation}
$$
with $\beta=e,\mu$. The above $\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \nu)^2$ is related to the $p\to K^+\nu$ decay width when the coefficients $a,b,d,e,g,h,j$ have similar absolute values9 and the terms with these coefficients interfere maximally constructively under the condition of $a\, (Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}+d\, (Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}=0$ and $b\, (Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}+e\, (Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}=0$, and when the contributions from left-handed dimension-5 operators to the $p\to K^+\bar{\nu}_\tau$ mode and those from right-handed ones interfere maximally constructively. Likewise, $\tilde{A}(p\to K^0 e^+_\beta)^2$ are related to the $p\to K^0 e^+_\beta$ decay widths when the coefficients $a,b,d,e$ have similar absolute values and the terms with these coefficients interfere maximally constructively under the condition of $a\, (Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}+d\, (Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}=0$ and $b\, (Y_{10})_{d_L s_L}+e\, (Y_{126})_{d_L s_L}=0$. Therefore, $\tilde{A}(p\to K^+ \nu)$ and $\tilde{A}(p\to K^0 e^+_\beta)$ allow us to estimate how much the texture of the GUT-scale Yukawa couplings $Y_{10}$, $Y_{126}$, and $Y_{120}$ contributes to the suppression of dimension-5 proton decays.

