\end{align}
$$
with $M_{\rm int}\ll2\times 10^{16}$. The left-hand side of Eq. (B.2) is the mass of the $({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)$ particle, which comes from $\Delta,\overline{\Delta}$. That of Eq. (B.3) is the mass of the $({\bf 6},{\bf 1},-\frac{2}{3})$ particle, which also comes from $\Delta,\overline{\Delta}$. Equation (B.4) and the relation $\lambda_{18}=\lambda_{20}=0$ guarantee that one eigenvalue of the mass matrix of the $({\bf 3},{\bf 2},\frac{1}{6})$ fields is about $M_{\rm int}$ (refer to Eq. (65) of Ref. [42]). Since $({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)+({\bf 6},{\bf 1},-\frac{2}{3})+({\bf 3},{\bf 2},\frac{1}{6})$ completes the 15 representation of $SU(5)$, the presence of one $({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)$, one $({\bf 6},{\bf 1},-\frac{2}{3})$, and one $({\bf 3},{\bf 2},\frac{1}{6})$ particles with mass of order $M_{\rm int}$ does not affect the gauge coupling unification irrespective of the value of $M_{\rm int}$. Also, the unified gauge coupling is perturbative around the GUT scale for any value of $M_{\rm int}$. Therefore, we can take $M_{\rm int}$ arbitrarily small.

The $({\bf 1},{\bf 3},1)$ particle, coming from $\Delta,\overline{\Delta}$, generates the Type-2 seesaw contribution to the active neutrino mass through the couplings of $\lambda_3\,\Delta H\Phi$ and $(\tilde{Y}_{126})_{ij}\Psi_i\overline{\Delta}\Psi_j$. The Type-2 seesaw contribution is estimated to be
(B.5)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
m_\nu^{\rm Type-2} \ \sim \ Y_{126} \, \lambda_3\, U_{H}U_{\Phi} \, \frac{v^2}{M_{\rm int}},\label{type2formula}
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $v=246$ GeV, and $U_{H},U_{\Phi}$ denote the ratio of MSSM Higgs $H_u$ in the $H$ and $\Phi$ fields, respectively. We have found numerically that $|U_{H}|$ is around 1, and that $|U_{\Phi}|$ varies over a wide range. The Type-1 seesaw contribution is estimated to be
(B.6)$$
\begin{eqnarray}
m_\nu^{\rm Type-1} \ \sim \ Y_DY_{126}^{-1}Y_D^{\rm T} \, \frac{v^2}{|v_R|},
\end{eqnarray}
$$
where $Y_D$ is given in Eq. (6). To compare the Type-2 and Type-1 seesaw contributions, we evaluate the largest singular value of $Y_{126}$ and that of $Y_DY_{126}^{-1}Y_D^{\rm T}$ for each fitting result (corresponding to each dot in Figs. 1 and 2). In fact, since we have not performed a fitting of coefficient $r_D$ in $Y_D$, we substitute $Y_D'Y_{126}^{-1}(Y_D')^{\rm T}$ with $Y_D'=Y_{10}-3r_2Y_{126}$ for $Y_DY_{126}^{-1}Y_D^{\rm T}$. We think that the singular values of $Y_D'Y_{126}^{-1}(Y_D')^{\rm T}$ approximate well those of $Y_DY_{126}^{-1}Y_D^{\rm T}$.
